[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The first crude hydrogen-powered helicopter flight&nbsp; recently took off in Quebec. The historic March&nbsp;&nbsp; 27th test flight was the first time a piloted&nbsp; hydrogen-powered helicopter went beyond a hover&nbsp;&nbsp; test, going through all the stages required&nbsp; for a full flight. Uh I think a lot of people&nbsp;&nbsp; underestimate what it takes to get a pilot on&nbsp; board such a vehicle with a hydrogen and all the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'safety aspect of of the demonstration. Hydrogen&nbsp; has long been touted as a more sustainable fuel&nbsp;&nbsp; source since its combustion produces only water&nbsp; and energy as byproducts. See those white plumes&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coming off the back of the helicopter? That&nbsp; isn\'t smoke, it\'s steam. But in order to be&nbsp;&nbsp; safe for human flight, burning clean isn\'t&nbsp; enough. Should there be an anticipated leak&nbsp;&nbsp; in one of the fuel lines, you want to ensure&nbsp; that the way the hydrogen will disperse into&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the atmosphere is done in a safe way. So with&nbsp; the proper amount of ventilation for example or&nbsp;&nbsp; under other circumstances where you would have a&nbsp; large quantity of hydrogen leaking from the system&nbsp;&nbsp; due to a malfunction uh you want to make sure&nbsp; that the venting system is physically located&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at the right spot on the aircraft to ensure that&nbsp; you\'re minimizing the risks of having hydrogen&nbsp;&nbsp; accumulation in any of the areas. Safety is always&nbsp; key in aviation and with hydrogen in particular,&nbsp;&nbsp; it\'s hard not to think of the most famous&nbsp; hydrogen- related aviation disaster in history,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the Hindenburg. A lot of consideration on proper&nbsp; segregation between the high voltage component&nbsp;&nbsp; and the hydrogen fuel feed system to minimize the&nbsp; risks of igniting the hydrogen in case of a leak.&nbsp;&nbsp; Aircraft that move forward like planes have air&nbsp; flowing constantly into the engine to cool it. But&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aircraft that hover in place like helicopters need&nbsp; to create cooling without that type of air flow.&nbsp;&nbsp; You may have noticed on some of the recordings and&nbsp; video of the flight that we had two big nestels on&nbsp;&nbsp; each side of the helicopter. So those are cooling&nbsp; pods. The helicopter being used was was a modified&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Robinson R44. And Robinson was a partner in this&nbsp; test flight along with a company called Unither&nbsp;&nbsp; Bio Electronics whose parent company is aimed at&nbsp; creating an unlimited supply of transplantable&nbsp;&nbsp; organs. And we\'ve basically decided to introduce&nbsp; sustainable aviation into that organ delivery&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'network. Sustainability also aligns with the&nbsp; company\'s mission as a public benefit corporation.&nbsp;&nbsp; The shorter flights and smaller aircrafts&nbsp; used for organ transplantation also make&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this a good platform for developing this type&nbsp; of sustainable flight technology. Hydrogen holds&nbsp;&nbsp; more energy per weight than batteries,&nbsp; making it a strong choice for aviation,&nbsp;&nbsp; but batteries are still helpful for managing&nbsp; parts of the flight that demand extra energy like&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takeoff and landing. The air taxi company Joby&nbsp; has also bet big on a hydrogen electric system,&nbsp;&nbsp; flying over 500 m using this combination in&nbsp; their uncrrewed demonstrator vehicle in 2024.&nbsp;&nbsp; Currently the the power system is very heavy.&nbsp; So in terms of a next step I think one of the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'challenges will be the reduction in weight of&nbsp; the fuel cell system including the cooling.&nbsp;&nbsp; There are very promising technologies out there&nbsp; basically result in a lower empty weight fraction&nbsp;&nbsp; of the aircraft even considering the fuel cell&nbsp; system weight etc. So freeing up some of the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'empty weight fraction and transferring that weight&nbsp; budget to the actual useful payload meaning pilots&nbsp;&nbsp; and organs. The main hurdles to more widespread&nbsp; hydrogen adoption as a fuel source in general and&nbsp;&nbsp; aviation in particular are building out the&nbsp; infrastructure, scaling up to reduce costs,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and satisfying safety regulations. The aviation&nbsp; industry has to really see a long-term vision&nbsp;&nbsp; like 20 30 years starting maybe in the next 5&nbsp; years with small aircrafts that only requires&nbsp;&nbsp; uh 20 kilogram of hydrogen for roughly 200&nbsp; nautical mile. In terms of the energy resilience&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and energy dominance, hydrogen has to be part of&nbsp; the solutions. And of course, you know, hydrogen&nbsp;&nbsp; is the most abundant element in the universe.&nbsp; What do you think of hydrogen-powered flight?&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let us know down in the comments and subscribe for&nbsp; more stories that make you say, "What the future?'
